Special permission bits: set-user-I-D, set-group-I-D, and sticky.

Beyond the ordinary read, write, and execute permissions, there are three special bits that change behaviour in particular ways, and they appear as modifiers on the execute positions in a long listing.

The first is set-user-I-D, the bit worth four thousand. When set on an executable file, the program runs as the file's owner rather than as whoever launched it. The classic example is the passwd command. An ordinary user needs to change their own password, which means writing to the shadow file, but that file is owned by root and writable by no one else. The solution is that passwd is owned by root and carries the set-user-I-D bit, so when you run it, the process runs as root and can update the shadow file. In a long listing this shows as a small s where the owner's execute letter would be. It is powerful and dangerous: a bug in a set-user-I-D root program is a path to full root access, so modern systems keep these binaries to a carefully audited minimum, and you can list them all with a find command searching for that permission.

The second is set-group-I-D, the bit worth two thousand, and it has two uses. On an executable file it works like set-user-I-D but for the group, which is rare. Far more common is its use on a directory, where it makes every file created inside inherit the directory's group rather than the creator's primary group. This is the standard recipe for a shared project directory: set the directory's group to the team and turn on this bit, and from then on everyone's files there belong to the team group, so all members can read and write each other's work. It shows as a small s in the group's execute position.

The third is the sticky bit, worth one thousand, used on a directory. It means that only a file's owner, or root, may delete or rename files within it, even though other users with write access can still create their own files there. The textbook example is the slash t-m-p directory, which everyone can write to but where no one can delete anyone else's files. In a long listing it appears as a t in the other-execute position.
